---
// src/pages/blog.astro
import MainLayout from "../../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
---

<MainLayout
  title="Astro and Tailwind: Building My Personal Web Portfolio"
  isBlogPost={true}
>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-8 md:px-16 py-10 mt-8 mb-16">
    <h1
      class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white my-6 text-center"
    >
      Astro and Tailwind: Building My Personal Web Portfolio
    </h1>

    <nav class="mb-10 flex justify-center">
      <div
        class="w-full max-w-md bg-indigo-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border border-indigo-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl shadow-md p-5"
      >
        <h2
          class="text-lg font-semibold text-indigo-900 dark:text-indigo-200 mb-3 text-center tracking-wide"
        >
          Table of Contents
        </h2>
        <ul
          class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-indigo-700 dark:text-indigo-300 text-base"
        >
          <li>
            <a
              href="#why-astro-and-tailwind"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >Why Astro and Tailwind?</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="#my-approach"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >My Approach</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="#challenges"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >Challenges and Solutions</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="#lessons-learned"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >Lessons Learned</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="#final-reflection"
              class="hover:text-indigo-900 dark:hover:text-white transition-colors duration-150 font-medium"
              >Final Reflection</a
            >
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </nav>

    <h2
      id="why-astro-and-tailwind"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      Why Astro and Tailwind?
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      When it came time to build my personal web portfolio, I knew I wanted to
      use modern, flexible tools that would help me achieve a fast, visually
      appealing site without compromising on performance. After considering my
      options, I settled on Astro and Tailwind CSS.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      Astro's ability to build static sites with a lightning-fast delivery was
      exactly what I needed. It supports multiple frameworks and allows me to
      write clean, minimal JavaScript. As for Tailwind, I was drawn to its
      utility-first approach. I wanted fine-grained control over my design, and
      Tailwind made it easy to build a custom, responsive layout without the
      overhead of a traditional CSS framework.
    </p>

    <h2
      id="my-approach"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      My Approach
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      Building my portfolio was an exciting opportunity to showcase not only my
      work but also my web development skills. I started with Astro's minimal
      setup to get a quick prototype running. The initial pages were basic: an
      about me section, a portfolio of my projects, and a contact form.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      With Tailwind, I immediately appreciated the utility-first design. Rather
      than diving into traditional CSS files and writing custom styles, I was
      able to apply classes directly in my HTML to create a responsive layout
      with grids, flexbox, and spacing utilities. The approach made it easy to
      rapidly iterate on design changes.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      I also integrated Astro components to keep my code modular and reusable.
      The ability to use components allowed me to create a consistent structure
      across the pages, like the footer and navigation, while also making it
      easier to update content across my entire site.
    </p>

    <h2
      id="challenges"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      Challenges and Solutions
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      Even though both Astro and Tailwind made development easier, I ran into
      some challenges along the way. One of the first obstacles I encountered
      was ensuring cross-browser compatibility and responsiveness. Even though
      Tailwind simplifies much of this, I had to tweak some of the design to
      make sure it worked well on older browsers. I used Tailwind's custom
      breakpoints and utility classes for responsiveness, but testing on various
      devices was crucial.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      Another challenge was keeping the site's performance in check. Astro's
      default setup is pretty efficient, but as I started adding images and
      third-party integrations (like analytics), I had to be mindful of
      optimizing assets. For images, I used Astro's built-in image optimization
      capabilities and the `@astro/image` package to ensure that images were
      served in the right format and size.
    </p>

    <h2
      id="lessons-learned"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      Lessons Learned
    </h2>
    <ul
      class="list-disc list-inside text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6 space-y-2"
    >
      <li>
        <strong>Start simple:</strong> It's easy to get carried away with too many
        features or complicated designs. I focused on simplicity first, and iterated
        on it over time.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Use Astro's built-in features:</strong> I didn't realize how much
        Astro can handle out of the box, especially in terms of optimizations. Make
        sure to take advantage of Astro's image optimization and static site generation
        features.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tailwind speeds up development:</strong> The utility-first approach
        isn't just a design pattern, it's a development pattern. I felt way more
        productive building out components with Tailwind than I would have with a
        custom CSS framework.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Performance matters:</strong> Even with a static site, performance
        is crucial. I learned that performance is something you need to think about
        from day one, especially when incorporating third-party elements.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2
      id="final-reflection"
      class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-200 mb-4 mt-10 scroll-mt-24"
    >
      Final Reflection
    </h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      Looking back, building my portfolio with Astro and Tailwind was a great
      decision. It gave me a chance to experiment with modern tools and gave me
      full control over both the design and performance. The best part was that
      it was fast to build and easy to maintain.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      My advice to anyone starting out with their own portfolio? Start with
      simple tools that empower you to build and scale. Don't overcomplicate
      things early on. Iterate, keep it clean, and focus on what's most
      important: your work.
    </p>

    <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
      Astro and Tailwind CSS made building my portfolio fun and efficient. If
      you're looking to create a fast, beautiful, and maintainable site, I
      highly recommend giving them a try!
    </p>

    <div class="flex justify-start gap-4 mt-16">
      <a
        href="/blog/uiux-workshop-highlights"
        class="text-indigo-700 dark:text-indigo-300 hover:underline font-medium flex items-center"
      >
        <svg
          class="mr-2 w-5 h-5"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          ><path
            stroke-linecap="round"
            stroke-linejoin="round"
            d="M15 19l-7-7 7-7"></path></svg
        >
        Previous: UI/UX Workshop Highlights
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</MainLayout>
